A system with 32-bit addresses, 1GB main memory, and 1MB page size will have an inverted page table that contains________ entries.

 1K

Correct answer

 4K

1M

 4G

Solution

Hide

Inverted page table = 1 entry per page frame 

Main memory = 1 G 

Page size = 1 M 

Therefore, number of page-frames = 1G / 1M = 1K (1024) entries.

 4.69, 9.38

 9.38, 4.69

2*4.69 cycles for L2

Question 51

You didn't Attempt

Consider a processor with 80 registers and an instruction set of size twelve. Each instruction has ve distinct elds, namely, opcode, two source register identifiers, one destination register identier, and a 15-bit immediate value. Each instruction must be stored in memory in a byte-aligned fashion. If a program has 100 instructions, the amount of memory (in bytes) consumed by the program text is _________.

-

Your answer

500

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

One instruction is divided into five parts,

(i) The opcode- As we have instruction set of size 12, an instruction opcode can be identified by 4 bits, as 2^4 = 16.

(ii) & (iii) Two source register identifiers- As there are total 80 registers, they can be identified by 7 bits. As they are two i.e. 7 bit + 7 bit.

iv) One destination register identifier- Again it will be 7 bits.

v) A 15 bit immediate value needs 15 bit.

 Adding them all we get,

4 + 7 + 7 + 7 + 15 = 40 bit = 40/8 byte = 5 bytes.

As there are 100 instructions, total size = 5*100 = 500 Bytes.

Question 58

semi group but not monoid

monoid but not group

Correct answer

a group

none of the above

Solution

Hide

The inverse of an odd integer with respective multiplication need not be an odd integer. 

 A is a monoid with respective multiplication but not a group.

Question 62

You didn't Attempt

Suppose that a message 1001 1100 1010 0011 is transmitted using Internet Checksum (4-bit word). What is the value of the checksum?

100100

101010

100010

Correct answer

None

Solution

Hide

For 4-bit checksum, we have to divide the message into 4-bit words and add all.

 1001 + 1100 + 1010 + 0011 = 100010

 We want 4-bit checksum, bring 10 down and so add

 0010 + 10 = 0100

 And checksum will be the complement of 0100 which is 1011.

Question 64

You didn't Attempt

What is the output of the following program?

#include <stdio.h>

#define x 4+2    

int main ()

{

int i;

i = x*x*x;

printf("%d",i);

return 0;

}

216

18

22

Correct answer

27

Solution

Hide

The C preprocessor will literally substitute all instances of x for 4+1, resulting in the following code:

i = 4+2*4+2*4+2;

Since * has precedence over +, this evaluates to:

i = 4+8+8+2;

and i gets the 22  value.
